10. Posterior notogastral sinus — Posterior to the valves, the plicature zone of 

Collohmannia

diffuses to become a large expanse of pale transitional cuticle, best seen in posterior view (
Fig. 10B
). The sinus may allow the notogaster to flex during contraction of the lateral compressor muscles, performing the same function as the terminal sinus or terminal fissure in Euphthiracaroidea (
Märkel 1964
; 
Sanders and Norton 2004
). Its form is consistent with Märkel’s observation that a sinus, rather than a fissure, is typical of those euphthiracaroid taxa having a broader notogaster.
